  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do parents support us?",
  "response": "Parents support their children for a variety of reasons, both emotional and practical. Here are some key motivations behind this support:\n\n1. **Unconditional Love:** Most parents have a deep emotional bond with their children and want to see them happy and successful. This love often drives them to provide support in many forms.\n\n2. **Nurturing Development:** Parents generally want to help their children grow into healthy, well-rounded individuals. They provide support to encourage development, learning, and personal growth.\n\n3. **Sense of Responsibility:** Many parents feel a duty to provide for their children, both financially and emotionally. This sense of responsibility motivates them to support their children's needs and aspirations.\n\n4. **Long-term Investment:** Parents often view their relationship with their children as an investment in the future. Supporting them in education, skills development, and other areas can lead to better opportunities for their children as adults.\n\n5. **Cultural and Social Expectations:** In many cultures, parents are expected to support their children as a societal norm. This can include emotional support, financial assistance, and guidance through challenging life events.\n\n6. **Desire for Success:** Parents often want their children to achieve their own goals and dreams. They may support them in pursuing education, hobbies, and interests that align with those aspirations.\n\n7. **Personal Experience:** Many parents draw on their own experiences to guide and support their children. They want to help their children avoid mistakes they made and navigate challenges more effectively.\n\n8. **Shared Happiness:** Parents often find joy in their children\u2019s successes and happiness. Supporting their children allows parents to share in those positive experiences.\n\nUltimately, parental support is multi-faceted and can vary greatly between different families and individual relationships.",
